deck_excerpt: Destiny Board Win ft. Junk Speeder
deck_description:
Hey there! Long time ago, I have won with Destiny Board as Panda. So, I decided to make this deck even simpler with Junk Speeder.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Draw until you find these combo pieces: Yata + Droll + Miracle Locus + Disturbance Strategy + Destiny Board. Then, set Disturbance + Miracle + Destiny and end your turn by discarding everything but Yata + Droll + Letters...

  • Before doing so, if you have "Chicken Game" present onboard, destroy it with Baronne and change the button on lower right corner of the screen to "ON". You need to be on your toes, should the opponent tries to disrupt you.
  • Although I couldn't draw letter "L" in this clip, it doesn't matter. I could have discarded Sword instead to not deck-out anyways. Besides, "Destiny Board" can find letters from hand and deck.

2) During your opponent's Standby Phase, activate Miracle to let your opponent draw a card. Then, activate Disturbance and chain into Droll. What will happen is Droll denies for either side to add any card to their hand. Therefore, by shuffling your opponent's hand into deck with Disturbance, they won't be able to draw/add any card afterwards, all thanks to Droll.

3) Your opponent has nothing to do but pass the turn back to you. That means you can start placing letters with "Destiny Board".

4) When it's your turn, Normal Summon Yata and place Sword on it. Attack the opponent with Yata, which denies your opponent from drawing any cards. When you end your turn, Yata returns to your hand and Sword is sent to GY, which makes Sword to be placed on top of your Main Deck to not deck-out by any means.

5) Repeat what was done in #3 + #4 until you win with "Destiny Board".

deck_name: Fonda Fontaine - Heal to Burn / Stun-lock (LOTD:LE)
deck_description:
In Yugioh GX, Fonda Fontaine is the head of the female Obelisk Blue dormitory at duel academy, while she is a gym instructor and the school's nurse too.

This is a guide for her deck profile.

This is not exactly an archetype, but cards with a similar goal, to heal your opponent's life points. This is not a very smart idea to start with, but with the help of "Bad reactions to simochi" or "Darklord Nurse Reficule" you can transform the healing to burning. There are many words to describe this kind of pseudo-archetype like: nurse-burn, anti-cure, anti-heal but I call it Heal-to-burn.

The problem with this deck as I said earlier is that it's not an archetype, which means there is not searchability through cards and we have to make it decent with generic support. Most of the times we need stun-lock, to find time to gather (draw) the cards we need.

While there are other burning cards that are doing their job better than this deck, you might be able to OTK (one turn kill) with this one. Cards like "Lava golem" and stun-lock can be enough to win vs CPU your offline duels, while the Timelords archetype is so strong that doesn't need this outdated mechanic to win at all. But if we run cards like them, then we lost the point of the theme of this deck, where the point is heal to burn.  

You can use cards like "Kuribandit" and "Jar of Avarice" to search through the deck easier, or even drawing cards through "into the void", "card of demise", "Ledger of Legerdemain" but it doesn't feel fair to have many copies of them, while they have drawbacks too...

I am very sorry to say these 2 things:

1) The main deck is not extremely optimized and I am not using the best cards (there is no spell/trap destruction).

2) The extra deck could be better, but I am kind of tired/bored to optimize it, while I run "Pot of Extravagance" which can destroy my try to make it better.

It might be better to run "gravity bind" or "Level Limit - Area B" as floodgates rather than stun-lock of battle phase.

Cards like "Lilith, Lady of Lament" and "Trap Trick" are quite good but they cannot search for "Bad reactions to simochi" at all.

You can always run an engine I've created that supports all trap cards, but it's quite slow. x3 "A Cat of Ill Omen", x3 "Super-Nimble Mega Hamster", x2 "Necrovalley", x2 "Gravekeeper's Commandant" which is a 10 card engine.

Kuribon might be a bad decision and you can remove it for something better like "dark cure".

Hey! I don't care what people says, Exodia isn't a trash deck nor it is a junk! Just keep drawing to see how easy it is, simple as that!

deck_excerpt: With explanations on why I chose to run certain things
deck_description:
The standard Dark World deck is a great option for budget players because it takes very little investment and still works to its fullest potential. Meta expensive cards like S:P ain't that much of an upgrade from Unicorn, and Thrust or Fuwalos are side deck cards at best.

This list is mainly focused on going first, putting up an oppressive board while hand-ripping your opponent. There are a few good extra deck options for going second but ideally, you should let the side deck do the work. Main deck is pretty standard, nothing out of the ordinary except for maybe Thunderbird which can be replaced with any card of your choice.

Losing Apollousa doesn't really affect DW because we can just make Gryphon instead. Tri-gate takes a bit more effort to set up, but the result is a stronger endboard than if you were to use any other rank 8 staple. That makes The Zombie Vampire our best rank 8 atm as it can help us play under Droll for a bit and still quite decent going second alongside with Dharc.

Magical Spring is very good in the current format against heavy face-up backrow decks like Snake-eyes and Yubel. Radian is a personal preference to out certain boss monsters while still keeping your normal summon. Puppetry is grave-hate therefore nothing more to say.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Creator: Cody Allan Rousseau

Tournament: Fargo WCQ Regional – October 19th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Welcome! In this deck, we will utilize Symphonic archetype and burn down the opponent with "Symph Amplifire". Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Link Summon Saryuja in a way that only Panda is present in Main Monster Zone (MMZ). Then, Special Summon Kuriboh with Saryuja. You can also Special Summon Black Luster Soldier with its ability to unlock "Primal Seed" loop and get rid of anything excess in MMZ if needed.

2) Place 1 x Amplifire + 2 x Generalprobe and Special Summon Guitariss from your hand. Next, Synchro Summon Rockks with Panda + Guitariss and activate Rockks to have Guitariss in your hand. 

3) Use Rockks to pop itself and place it on Pendulum Zone besides Guitariss. If you have done everything right, you should have 3 x MMZ reserved for Basses + Synthess + Gaap. Pendulum Summon these three.

4) Activate Synthess to copycat Basses. Then, use Synthess + Basses. If you have noticed, from #2 to #4, activating "Symphonic Warrior" cards accumulates counters on Amplifire and Generalprobe. So, why not start using counters to burn with Amplifire? Know that after using Amplifire, activate 2nd copy to reset Amplifire and use its burn ability again.

5) Activate Lance and target on Gaap. Next, play "Book of Eclipse", which results into flipping down anything but Gaap thanks to Lance. However, Gaap lets them open up. This step is needed to reset Synthess and Basses in order to repeat what was explained in #4 until your opponent is dead.

deck_description:
Welcome! This deck is a callback to one I did ages ago. At least this version looks easier, don't you think?

 

Gameplan

1) When you have Ancient present, raise its level by 1 with "Synchro World" and Special Summon Bone Tower with Ancient. Then, pass Bone Tower to the opponent with "Shien's Spy"...

  • If your opponent's side is full, feel free to use Coral and Legatia to clear Main Monster Zones.

2) Activate "Zombie World" and "Jackpot 7" from your hand. Then, replace Librarian with "Stardust Synchron". What will happen is that you start milling "Jackpot 7" with Bone Tower. Even though monster you have summoned isn't Zombie by default, "Zombie World" overwrites this condition. Since "Jackpot 7" cards were milled by your opponent thanks to Bone Tower, you will win the duel!

3) Synchro Summon Crimson or Legatia with Ancient as Level 8 Non-Tuner and Stardust Synchron as Level 4 Tuner to mill last "Jackpot 7". Victory is yours!

deck_excerpt: Morphing Jar Mill OTK ft. Junk Speeder
deck_description:
Greetings! Do you want to experience Empty Jar deck? Well, this deck is for you. If you want to look at Panda version, click here!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Synchro Summon Ravenous with Librarian + Stardust Synchron. Then, discard Wanghu + Wattfox + Sword + MJ + MJ #2 with Ravenous and at End Phase due to large hand size. However, before that, set Igknight Reload and all Traps...

  • You need to have 3 x Main Monster Zones (MMZ) free from your opponent's side. If they are full, feel free to use Coral/Ravenous/Legatia.

2) If you have Pendulum Monster in your hand, during your opponent's Draw Phase, activate these cards in order explained below:

  1. Igknight Reload
  2. Ravenous >>> Discard Pendulum + Any
  3. Powerful Rebirth >>> Wattfox
  4. Give and Take >>> Wanghu
  5. Reverse Reuse >>> MJ #2 as face-down and MJ as face-up
  6. All-Out Attacks

3) Here is what is going on...

  • In the first two actions, "Igknight Reload" has been activated to not let you draw any cards via MJ. Even though you couldn't reveal Pendulum Monster in your hand to shuffle it and draw cards due to Ravenous, game considers "Igknight Reload" as perfectly resolved.
  • As for the rest; Wanghu destroys Wattfox, which shuts down anything your opponent can try to break you, including hand-traps. Then, via All-Out Attacks, MJ #2 will flip face-up and you can start milling your opponent with MJ.

4) After everything is done in #2 and #3, rather than both players drawing 5 cards via MJ, only your opponent can thanks to "Igknight Reload". This step will go on until your opponent has nothing to draw and you win the game!

deck_excerpt: Jackpot 7 FTK ft. Junk Speeder + Needle Worm
deck_description:
Hey there! Similar to this setup I did, we can win yet another time as Junk Speeder via "Jackpot 7".

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have Circle present and drawn your whole Main Deck, bring forth Needle and pass it to the opponent with "Shien's Spy"...

  • If your opponent's side is full, feel free to use Coral/Ravenous/Legatia to clear Main Monster Zones.
  • You can also win with Hiro or Morphing Jar #2 instead of Needle. All you need to do is replace Circle with Ancient. However, it can be costly as Ancient is UR while Circle is R to craft. Feel free to check them in Side Deck.

2) Replace Librarian with "Stardust Synchron" and Synchro Summon Pluto with Stardust Synchron + Level 1 Non-Tuner. Then, activate Pluto to place Needle or Hiro face-down.

3) Play all three "Jackpot 7" cards to shuffle them back into Main Deck. Next, open up Needle or Hiro or MJ#2 with "Book of Taiyou". Whether you have sent "Jackpot 7" from Main Deck to GY with Needle for certain or with MJ#2 which requires luck or drawn from Main Deck to your hand and sent them to GY straight away from there with Hiro, you will trigger "Jackpot 7". Reason is that your opponent sent all three "Jackpot 7" cards to GY, which results into your victory!

deck_excerpt: Standard Mimighoul lineup backed by a generic earth engine.
deck_description: Mimighoul has a lot of powerful interruptions requiring very little setup, but with the new support in ROTA they have more explosive lines available with enough extention. Enter the Vernusylphs. The vernusylphs can work all sorts of earth names into rotation, including more mimighouls, and give the deck access to a couple of diversified interactions, from mudora in GY, to fenrir control, and sometimes even a negate! individually though, the vernusylphs act as a way to bait interaction, push through plays, and recur resources from the gy, helping the deck break boards going second. This deck is currently a work in progress but seems off to a good start.

deck_excerpt: Don't even look at this, it's nearly a decade old and only for archival purposes
deck_description: It's an old deck I played once, just showing a friend

In my opinion the best earth machine build out there. An increased deck size decreases chances of drawing box or unclaspare, while increasing starter count to 14 gives it 85% chance to draw a starter. Including new Clockwork Knight gives interesting lines with Scrap Recycler. Best combo is Redeployment + Switchyard + 1 discard, which results in 2 Super Dora, Knuckle + Bullet loop, Regulus, and Citadel in the gy. Pretty resiliant to handtraps if ordered correctly. Engine isn't bad going into boards, but pairing it with 14 non-engine makes it consistent at breaking boards. Switchyard makes rank 10 plays much easier. Machinas are best into boards, and infinitracks are great for consistency and recursion. Sargas is great on the crack back, where you can insulate otk line with Regulus. Cards are relatively cheap, so this is a budget deck that gets better and more fun with more repetitions.

deck_description:
Dragon link supports a lot of rulers as it allows you to bin rulers with the ravine which is built into the combo.

Tempest -> Search for any of your combo pieces (e.g. metal dragon or you can search out the tuner if you don't have it)

Armed dragons -> Discardables + searcher for tempest (note: its probably a good idea to add a wind dragon that can do something more than being material because when you already have what you need they just turn into material-although this is kind of fine)

Another way to get to your tuners from the combo is to bin the red rose and if you've drawn a garnet. You can bin something like abs or use red rose shoot to revive the red rose. Otherwise make pisty and then triple burst and then use pisty effect to get back the red rose. Darkness metal is just there to do something with the leftover link material- might as well convert it to an extender because once youve gotten to rom+pisty+striker you have no other use for the 3 link materials. Make triple burst to give them all the same attribute then link into black metal.

deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will win with a rare to be found win-condition called Vennominaga. If interested, keep on reading!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant at least three flowers to opposing side with "Black Garden". Usually, it can be done with the following:

  • Special Summon with Ancient.
  • Special Summoning "Stardust Synchron" from GY.
  • Ritual Summoning Amorphactor by tributing Stardust Synchron from field and Coatl from hand.

2) Ritual Summon Amorphactor with "Earth Chant" to skip your opponent's Main Phase 1. Then, activate "Seal of Orichalcos" to destroy all of your monsters.

3) With your side being empty, you can play "A Wild Monster Appears!" to cheat out Vennominaga. Next, set "Yang Zing Unleashed" and end your turn.

4) When it's your opponent's Draw Phase, activate the Trap you set, which locks your opponent into Battle Phase. Since you have only Vennominaga, that means your opponent has to tackle into her with flowers. If you kill three of them, you win the duel!

  • 1 x Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon >>> 30 UR
  • 1 x Crimson Dragon >>> 30 UR

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Which strategy can reliably maindeck the new extremely strong handtraps from Rage of the Abyss? Tenpai!
deck_description:
Which strategy can reliably maindeck the new extremely strong handtraps from Rage of the Abyss? That deck would be Tenpai Dragon! Tenpai always plays "blind second," rendering the Mulcharmy cards always live, and even if you're forced to go 1st, you can chain Mulcharmies to your Hieratic Seals when it leaves the field!

Arguably the most powerful and game-warping card released in a decade, Fuwalos' draw 1 everytime your opponent summons from deck and extra deck finds its best home in Tenpai! The Light/Wind/Earth attribute effect lock that Dominus Impulse forces on the Tenpai duelist doesn't matter to the pilot, since most the monster attribute effects you use for the duel will be fire anyways!

Using the combined power of Fuwalos, Impulse, and the extremely potent Tenpai OTK strategy, you'll be getting freewins and quick games all the time!

If you want a detailed guide and combo on how to use the deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

deck_excerpt: Deck built using the YUGIOH wiki going for the top played cards to put into a battle box.
deck_description: Deck built using the YUGIOH wiki going for the top played cards to put into a battle box.

Now, I know what you're probably thinking: "Why is this idiot not running tract, lurrie and the 3rd bonfire"? Well, the reason I'm not playing bonfire is because I just kinda wanted to get the deck down to 40 cards because I couldn't make a 41 card deck look good, which is very important to me. However, for the other two (as well as a few other things) I do have legitimate reasons for not running them, which is the first thing I'll go into.

1 - More Fiendsmith engine (Tract, Lurrie, Sanct, Necroquip Wave High)

     Obviously given that this is a Fiendsmith deck instead of a Fire King deck, you would expect it to be running all of these staples of the Fiendsmith engine, right? However, there is one important detail that heavily influences my decision: Almost nobody is running Nib this format. Wave High is certainly a very good card, but it's main use is undeniably to stop Nibiru. But unfortunately, Silvia has taken his job from him and so now Nibiru is suddenly a lot less useful. And you would be right to think that having 2 ways to stop Nib isn't inherently bad, but the thing that I'm really getting at is that there are so many ways to stop Nib now that running it would be a liability, therefore I don't see much use in running Wave High anymore, or Necroquip by proxy.

     And you might think that's also the entire reason I'm not running Lurrie/Tract/Sanct, but you'd actually be wrong, because there's a whole other reason, and it's that they're basically useless. You can make Wave High on top of the current board by just drawing Lacrima or Engraver and tributing/sending them to use the main Azamina combo if you run Agnumday (which I'll get into later, don't worry). AND, on top of that, the Wave High turbo combo makes Wave High as the 6 summon, so if you do that first than you lose a negate because they'll just Nib after you summon Engraver, and the 2nd negate from Wave High is now gone.

2 - Knightmare Phoenix

     I will admit, I have a bit of a grudge with this card. I just don't think it's very helpful a lot of the time, but even I can't deny that it's a good card which is worth running.

3 - Kashtira engine

     Mid as hell tbh

Now that I've gotten that out of the way, it's time for the fun part: The cards that I AM using, when any sane person would say not to.

1 - Morrian

     To get the elephant in the room out of the way, there are a couple reasons behind running Morrian. First off, it's the best card to search with Silvia (I bet you forgot it could do that, didn't you?) and in case you were wondering, yes it does come up, but I will admit that a lot of the times it comes up are going 2nd against another Snake-Eye deck, because 99% of players will use Princess on Silvia right when they get the chance. The 2nd reason is the 2nd effect, because that means it's essentially a free discard to summon Diabellstar since you can get it right back after summoning an Azamina monster, and this card specifically is a very good option for mitigating that cost because of interactions with Debtors that I'll get into later. But as for that 1st effect... it really is quite mediocre, huh?

2 - Subversion

     First off, if your starter is Diabellstar (not Seeker) then Poplar has nothing to add when you summon it with Flamberge turn 2, so running another Snake-Eye spell is definitely a good idea. But as for Subversion specifically, it's actually a surprisingly good board breaker, both to draw and to search. And to remind you, it can be searched not only by Poplar, but also by Diabellstar, Rcielago and... well, Rcielago because it's also a Sinful Spoils. You'd really be surprised by how good a very searchable 1 for 1 trade actually is going 2nd, and it's also a good thing to add going 1st if you have extras, because the other option would be something like another Seeker.

3 - Agnumday

     You might think that running Agnumday when I have so little of the rest of the Fiendsmith engine is contradictory, but actually it isn't. If you go through the main Azamina combo that uses 2 discards (which you have to go through if you opened Deception and no other combo), you end up with 2 extra pieces of material and Agnumday is unironically the best thing to use one of them for (the other free material isn't used, in case you were wondering). You can just use a Snake-Eye that you summoned with Flamberge + Sequence to make it, then you just link it away anyways. To be specific about it, the point of Agnumday is that on turn 2 if your opponent outs Desirae, you can use Lacrima to summon Agnumday and then use Agnumday to summon Desirae.

     Obviously going into Agnumday isn't always worth it, but if you go first and you draw something like Seeker + Fuwalos + Fuwalos, then you might as well, huh?

4 - Dominus Impulse (x2)

     The idea behind Impulse is that going 2nd, you can side out Lacrima and Engraver for it. The only things it stops in this deck are Fuwalos and the Fiendsmith engine, so you can just shotgun any Fuwalosses and not go into the Fiendsmith engine, and lets be honest here how often do you go into Desirae going 2nd? You could run something like Nib instead, but that's a lot of risk when this deck doesn't even have 3 Imperm.

5 - Debtors (x2)

     The main reason to run Debtors is to stop Impulse, but it also has a very good use in recycling Silvia on turn 1. It's pretty simple to see the application in chaining Debtors to an Impulse that's chaining to your Hallowed, but Debtors can do so much more than that. For example, the simple way you can use it to recycle Silvia is to send it with Diabellstar and then use the 2nd effect to summon her back. But, the other thing you can do is, instead of using the Hallowed 2nd effect to put back Rcielago then using it to make Silvia, you can use the Debtors to make it instead. Then, if you have to use Silvia on turn 1, you can then use the Hallowed 2nd effect to put back Silvia and use it with a Sinful Spoils in your hand (something like Morrian or Subversion) to get her back, AND you'll also still have the Debtors in GY to get Silvia back on turn 3. Alternitavely, you could just run a 2nd Silvia and then you wouldn't need the Sinful Spoils in hand, and could just use Deception on the opponent's turn.

6 - Goddess

WHITE WOMAN JUMPSCARE!

deck_excerpt: Give me something good to eat!
deck_description: Go second, break boards, and mill to win! Ween, the Spirit of Treats is an alternate win condition whose normal/special summon effect gets stronger if there's a ton of zombies in your graveyard! Use Mezuki's effect to special summon Ween from your graveyard!

deck_excerpt: Trick or treat! Smell my feet!
deck_description: Hallo, the Spirit of Tricks is a dark fiend with 0/0 stats, so she naturally fits into Unchained Yubel decks as an alternate win condition. You can search Hallo for with Nightmare Throne's effect. If you normal or special summon Hallo while you have multiple fiends, preferably 3+, in your graveyard, then she will either gain a ton of attack or inflict a massive amount of effect damage. She can also send an opponent's monster to the graveyard if she's destroyed by battle or by a card like Nightmare Pain or Nightmare Throne.

I initially tried to build this with a Red-eyes Fusion package, but the restrictaion on its fusion spell is just maddening, so here we are with an engine that is both more flexible and less painful to use.

Notes:

- Primite Roar or Lordly Load can fetch any monster needed for Max Metalmorph, but the hard once per turn clause on Max Metalmorph led me to only keep Fulmetal dragon;

- Branded Fusion can set the grave with any Attribute for Imperial Dragon (Primite Roar to fetch any Normal monster which means any attribute, then Branded Fusion to summon Sprind to get that Normal monster in the graveyard);

- Black Metal Dragon into Striker Dragon to prock its search effect, gets you Fullmetal Dragon;

- Mirrorjade effect to foolish Rindbrumm, then Rindbrumm effect to rez Albaz to make Sprind with an opponent's monster is basically a 3 for 0 in terms of card advantage.

The real drawback to the Metalmorph and Primite cards is that the deck has almost nothing to go second except for Dragoon/Mirrorjade and Drillbeam and thus only really plays on turn four; so it your opponent has any quick effect to destroy your (mainly trap) action, you will not do much.

deck_excerpt: Hey Tenpai, make Mannadium go first, I DARE YOU!
deck_description:
Hey Tenpai, make Mannadium go first, I DARE YOU! *Creates a board with 8 interruptions*

I chose this deck to combat the excess of Tenpai players on ladder, since they make you go first and it's basically a freewin if you're playing a FTK board deck like Mannadium. For the October 2024 version of this deck, I opted to put in "A Hero Lives" package with Elemental Hero Prisma for extra gas, since it copies Visas Starfrost's name and from there you can one card combo without even using your normal summon. This version of the strategy also maindecks Mannadium Reframing, a searchable omni-negate counter trap since it helps stave off those pesky boardbreaker spells Tenpai likes using so much. Even if you're not facing Tenpai, Mannadium has a ton of potential to power through established boards and to play through handtraps with its immense boardbuilding ability.

If you want a thorough guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article!

deck_excerpt: non-meta, pure deck,  meant just for fun!

deck_description: Excited for the new support for the gladiators! It's been 5 years since the last support. It's time for battle!

The Lair of Darkness archetype actually pairs really well with Primite cards since Lordly Lode requies you not to activate effects of special summoned monsters on your field, and the Lair monsters can play from the hand or during the opponent's turns :

- Ahrima is mostly used to find the Lair of Darkness

- Lilith has a Quick effect, though it is still preferable to prock it on our turn so that the trap she sets can be activated during the following turn

- Diabolos can be summoned during the opponent's turn

I included a small Metalmorph package because it synergizes so well with the Primite archetype and gives access to aither a negate or a pop plus a tower/beater.

Tha plan is mostly to use Lair of Darkness to tribute (for cost!) our opponent's monsters to activate powerful effects (mostly Ballista and Lilith in the main, but for game 2 and 3 we get access to the Viruses in the side to tailor our threats to the deck we face), all while using Primite and Metalmorph cards to defend ourselves.

deck_excerpt: Geargia Rampage: unleash powerful combos with versatile Machine monsters for any Duelist!
deck_description: Geargia Decks are one of the hottest tournament Deck themes for the Yu-Gi-Oh! TRADING CARD GAME, and are at the core of the brand new Geargia Rampage Structure Deck! Geargia cards are versatile and really good: their strategy is based around teamwork and Geargia monsters can Special Summon more Geargia monsters, or add them to your hand for free. Since Geargia monsters are also Machine-Type, you can even use them with other Machine monsters from other Decks to perform some explosive combos. Things only get better for Geargia strategies with the introduction of three new monster cards including a brand new Geargia Xyz Monster that can shut down your opponent’s cards during battle. New Duelists can now get their hands on these popular cards while advanced Duelists can support their existing Geargia Decks or other Machine-Type Decks to bolster their strategies.

deck_excerpt: Elemental HERO Decks return in HERO Strike: unleash powerful Fusion and Masked HERO transformations—get your game on!
deck_description:
Elemental HERO Decks make a mighty return to the Yu-Gi-Oh! TRADING CARD GAME in the HERO Strike Structure Deck! Modeled after Jaden Yuki’s Deck from the Yu-Gi-Oh! GX anime and manga series, the HERO Strike Structure Deck contains new cards with new ways to Summon them!

Elemental HERO Decks rely on the power of Fusion Summoning, allowing you to fuse monsters together with Spell Cards like Polymerization and Miracle Fusion to Summon Elemental HERO Fusion Monsters; in the HERO Strike Structure Deck, brand new Spell Cards are introduced to give your monsters a new secret identity as a Masked HERO monster as well! As a special bonus, the HERO Strike Structure Deck also includes one new Ultra Rare Card and four new Super Rare Cards, bringing the total count to 45 Cards!

Whether you’re an old-time Yu-Gi-Oh! GX fan, or you’re discovering the Elemental HERO strategy for the first time, you can now wield the power of these marvelous heroes for yourself. Get Your Game On!

deck_excerpt: Synchron Extreme Structure Deck: unleash powerful Synchro Summons with 10 brand-new cards inspired by Yusei Fudo’s iconic strategy!
deck_description:
Synchro Summoning is at the forefront of the new Synchron Extreme Structure Deck! Inspired by Yusei Fudo’s Deck from the Yu-Gi-Oh! 5D’s anime and manga series, the Synchron Extreme Structure Deck contains a whopping 10 brand-new cards, including 3 brand-new Synchro Monsters!

Synchro Summoning depends on swarming the playing field with lower level Monsters like Speed Warrior and Junk Synchron, letting you easily Synchro Summon a more powerful Monster to the field. In the Synchron Extreme Structure Deck, brand new Monsters like Jet Synchron and Rush Warrior are introduced, letting you more easily Summon Synchro Monsters like Stardust Warrior, a behemoth with 3000 ATK and the power to prevent opposing Special Summons or Special Summon your other Synchro Monsters! The Synchron Extreme Structure Deck also includes 2 Ultra Rare Cards and 3 new Super Rare cards!

This 44-card Deck includes cards that meet the needs of players new and old, including a record-setting 10 new cards for a Structure Deck! This set will also have excellent synergy with Legendary Collection 5D's.

deck_excerpt: Master of Pendulum: unleash mystifying Pendulum, Synchro, and Xyz strategies with powerful new Spellcaster cards!
deck_description:
New Pendulum Monsters arise in the Master of Pendulum Structure Deck, bringing with them powerful effects and strategies to mystify your opponent! In addition to these monsters, the Master of Pendulum Structure Deck contains 10 brand-new cards, including brand-new Synchro and Xyz Monsters!

Spellcasters abound in the Master of Pendulum Structure Deck, empowering you with the ability to destroy opponent cards with the tip of a hat! Dragonpulse Magician and Dragonpit Magician do just that, by discarding Pendulum Monsters to target your opponent’s Monster or Spell/Trap card and destroy them! The Pendulum Call Spell Card lets you pick a perfect pair of Magician Pendulum Monsters while protecting the Magician cards in your Pendulum Zones. This formidable Structure Deck even lets you dabble in Fusion, Synchro, and Xyz Summoning and includes one of each kind of monster! Try your hand at Synchro Summoning Odd-Eyes Meteorburst Dragon or double down on Level 7 monsters to Xyz Summon Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon!

This 43-card Deck has great synergy with the Clash of Rebellions and Dimension of Chaos booster sets, and includes cards that new and experienced Duelists will enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Emperor of Darkness: summon ancient Monarchs and dominate the field with powerful Tribute strategies!
deck_description:
With the addition of several brand-new cards and a ready-to-play Deck that makes these Monsters more powerful than ever, ancient Monarchs are back to rule with the Emperor of Darkness Structure Deck!

The Emperor of Darkness Structure Deck is filled with some of the most imposing Monsters ever made, and they demand Tribute! Monarchs are high-Level monsters that unleash their devastating elemental powers when Tributes are offered to Summon them. Strike a combo using the mighty Erebus the Underworld Monarch with new support cards like Eidos the Underworld Squire or The Prime Monarch, to thwart your opponent’s strategy and reinforce your Deck!

In addition to this 41-card Deck, Duelists can add a brand-new Token card to their collection. With a mix of new and classic cards, this popular theme appeals to both beginning and existing players.
Stall with Lich long enough to steamroll with Wights + Grass

deck_name: Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck
deck_excerpt: Rise of the True Dragons: power up with high-Level Dragons and unstoppable Graveyard summons to dominate the field!
deck_description:
The second half of 2016 is a season for Dragons in the Yu-Gi-Oh! TRADING CARD GAME! Following up on May’s re-launch of the legendary “Blue-Eyes” theme in Shining Victories, July brings more *oomph* to Duelists’ Dragon Decks with the Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck!

This 41-card Deck is the second of four releases this year to celebrate the high-Level Dragon strategy pioneered by Seto Kaiba on the original Yu-Gi-Oh! animated TV series, and includes new high-Level Dragons that banish opposing cards when Summoned, and gain more Attack Points for each card they banish. Also included are new Dragon devotee monsters – easy-to-Summon low-Level Warriors that help get your high-Level Dragons into play quickly. The best part is that these utility Warriors work with ANY high-Level Dragons, including Dragons from other Decks and booster sets.

The real gem of Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck is a new Spell Card that Summons any Level 7 or 8 Dragon directly from the Graveyard, with no restrictions, and can be used afterwards to protect your Dragons from being destroyed, with no drawbacks or limitations. A must-have card for every Dragon Deck!

Rise of the True Dragons Structure Deck contains a 41-card Deck with 2 Ultra Rares, 3 Super Rares, and 36 Commons, plus a new Dragon Token Card celebrating over a decade of devotion to Duelists’ Dragon Decks!
